Passwords and Secrets Policy
Purpose 
The purpose of this Passwords and Secrets Policy is to establish guidelines and procedures for the secure management and usage of passwords and other sensitive credentials within [Client]. This policy aims to protect against unauthorized access, data breaches, and ensure the confidentiality and integrity of [Client]'s systems and information. 

Scope 
This policy applies to all employees, contractors, vendors, and any other individuals who have access to and use [Client]'s systems, applications, and resources that require passwords or other sensitive credentials. 

Policy Statements 
3.1 Password Complexity and Strength 
a. Password Complexity: Users shall create passwords that meet minimum complexity requirements, including a combination of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters. 
b. Password Length: Passwords shall be a minimum of 12 characters in length, with longer passwords encouraged. 
c. Password Strength Assessment: a mechanism to assess and enforce password strength during the password creation and reset process should be established.

3.2 Password Storage and Protection 
a. Password Encryption: Passwords shall be securely stored using industry-standard encryption algorithms to protect them from unauthorized access or disclosure. 
b. Secure Password Storage: Passwords shall be stored in a centralized, secure password management system or encrypted database, accessible only to authorized personnel. 
c. Prohibition of Plain Text Passwords: Plain text passwords or storing passwords in clear text form are strictly prohibited. 


3.3 Password Usage and Management 
a. Password Sharing: Users shall not share their passwords with anyone, including colleagues, friends, or family members. 
b. Individual Account Usage: Each user shall have their individual account and associated credentials. Sharing of user accounts is prohibited. 
c. Password Expiration: Passwords shall have a defined expiration period, after which users will be prompted to change their passwords.
d. Password Reuse: Users shall not reuse passwords across different systems or accounts. Unique passwords should be used for each application or service. 
e. Multifactor Authentication (MFA): is to be implemented and encouraged for systems and applications whenever possible. 


3.4 Secrets Management 
a. Sensitive Credentials: Other sensitive credentials, such as API keys, cryptographic keys, or database passwords, shall be securely stored, managed, and rotated as per industry best practices. 
b. Access Control: Access to sensitive credentials shall be strictly limited to authorized personnel on a need-to-know basis. 


3.5 Password Reset and Recovery 
a. Password Reset Process: a well-defined password reset process should be in place to verify the identity of users before resetting passwords. 
b. Forgotten Passwords: Users who forget their passwords shall follow the established password recovery process to regain access to their accounts. 


Responsibilities 4.1 Management 
a. Management shall ensure the implementation and enforcement of this Passwords and Secrets Policy.
 b. Management shall provide necessary resources, support, and authority to maintain secure password and secrets management practices. 

4.2 IT Department 
a. The IT department shall be responsible for the implementation and management of secure password storage systems, password policies, and secrets management practices. 
b. The IT department shall enforce password complexity requirements, conduct periodic password audits, and provide user awareness training on password best practices. 


4.3 Users 
a. Users must adhere with this policy and the password and secrets management practices outlined herein. 
b. Users shall promptly report any suspected unauthorized access or compromise of passwords or secrets to the IT department or the designated point of contact. 


Policy Review 
This Passwords and Secrets Policy shall be reviewed periodically, or as deemed necessary, to ensure its effectiveness and alignment with [Client]'s business objectives and evolving security requirements. 

